{# Overview #}
<section class="project-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="diamond">◆</span> OVERVIEW
    </div>
    <h2 class="section-heading">Where it started and <em>where it went</em></h2>
    <p>Lumen Learning's Introductory Psychology course began in its earliest phases as an OER-focused adaptation of OpenStax Psychology content on Lumen's original Candela platform. Over time, through two more platform generations, it evolved into a full courseware system with original content, thousands of assessment items, instructor-ready classroom activities, and regular updates tied to current research.</p>
    <p>Introductory Psychology is now Lumen Learning's highest-enrolled non-math course, and I continue to develop and refine it, with a focus on data-driven improvements in areas.</p>
  </div>
</section>

{# Course Design #}
<section class="project-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="diamond">◆</span> COURSE DESIGN
    </div>
    <h2 class="section-heading">Designing around <em>the learner experience</em></h2>
    <p>I designed the course architecture to support a clear and consistent learning experience for both students and instructors. Each of the 16 modules follows the same predictable structure — Readiness Check, Background You'll Need, Learn It content, embedded practice, Apply It activities, Self-Check formative quizzes, review materials, and a Summative Quiz — so students quickly understand how to navigate the course and what is expected of them.</p>
    <p>The design draws on the APA Guidelines for the Undergraduate Psychology Major (Version 3.0) and integrates the seven APA Integrative Themes throughout. Rather than appearing as isolated concepts, the themes are woven into assessments, module introductions, and activities to help students connect individual topics to broader ideas about human behavior and psychological science.</p>
    <figure class="project-figure">
      <img src="/images/projects/psych/slide-04.png" alt="Course approach slide showing APA 7 Integrative Themes" />
      <figcaption>The seven APA Integrative Themes served as a genuine design scaffold, embedded at the assessment and activity level throughout all 16 modules.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>
</section>

{# Content Development #}
<section class="project-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="diamond">◆</span> CONTENT DEVELOPMENT
    </div>
    <h2 class="section-heading">A course that treats students <em>like whole people</em></h2>
    <p>I led the development of the course from concept through implementation, collaborating closely with subject matter experts including Patrick Carroll (University of Texas at Austin), Jessica Traylor (Gordon State College), and nearly a dozen others. My role involved recruiting and coaching SMEs, translating disciplinary expertise into accessible instructional materials, and ensuring that all content aligned with both pedagogical best practices and Lumen's product goals.</p>

    <div class="callout-quotes">
      <blockquote class="callout-quote">
        <p>"Wendy's coaching has been the most practical feedback I've received in the world of higher education curriculum. The way you offer constructive feedback without direct criticism is encouraging."</p>
        <cite>— Subject matter expert collaborator, first-year full-time professor</cite>
      </blockquote>
      <blockquote class="callout-quote">
        <p>"Working with Wendy from Lumen was amazing! Besides being a content expert, she is an amazing coach. If you have the opportunity to work with her on anything, I would highly recommend it."</p>
        <cite>— Jessica Traylor, Subject Matter Expert</cite>
      </blockquote>
    </div>

    <p>Content development focused on making psychology readable, relatable, and culturally grounded. Dense textbook passages were restructured into more approachable sections with clear headings and examples that connect psychological concepts to everyday experiences. The course addresses WEIRD bias (the tendency for psychology research to over-represent Western, Educated, Industrialized, Rich, and Democratic populations) along with representation in the history of psychology and culturally competent practice, woven throughout rather than siloed.</p>
    <p>One example is the <em>Psych in Real Life</em> feature: original narrative scenarios developed with Pat Carroll that illustrate concepts like behavior therapy, memory processes, and social influence. Students aren't just reading a definition — they're following Miriam, a business student working through her fear of public speaking or learning about Hamlin and Winn's research on moral development in infants.</p>

    <figure class="project-figure">
      <img src="/images/projects/psych/slide-12.png" alt="Content in text slide showing Learn It, Apply It, and Fresh Take structure" />
      <figcaption>Every topic has multiple entry points: Learn It for core content, Apply It for application, and Fresh Take for students who want a different perspective.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>
</section>

{# Instructor Experience #}
<section class="project-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="diamond">◆</span> INSTRUCTOR EXPERIENCE
    </div>
    <h2 class="section-heading">Building a course faculty <em>actually want to teach</em></h2>
    <p>Because many instructors teaching Introductory Psychology are adjunct faculty with limited preparation time, a major focus of the project was building resources that make the course easier to teach. Every module includes a complete Instructor Guide with learning outcomes, summaries, and detailed descriptions of classroom activities grounded in evidence-based teaching practices. These guides explain not only how to run an activity but also the pedagogical reasoning behind it.</p>
    <p>Each module also includes a ready-to-use PowerPoint deck, allowing instructors to adopt the materials immediately or customize them to fit their teaching style. The goal was a system where instructors can spend less time preparing materials and more time interacting with students.</p>

    <figure class="project-figure">
      <img src="/images/projects/psych/slide-15.png" alt="Instructor Guides with Module 8 detail" />
      <figcaption>Instructor Guides cover learning outcomes, module summaries, and activity-by-activity implementation notes, all grounded in evidence-based teaching practices.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>
</section>

{# Iteration & Improvement #}
<section class="project-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-label">
      <span class="diamond">◆</span> ITERATION &amp; IMPROVEMENT
    </div>
    <h2 class="section-heading">A course that <em>keeps getting better</em></h2>
    <p>This course has evolved through three platform generations and continues to be updated regularly. Recent update cycles introduced new research and contemporary topics including psychedelic-assisted therapy, the replication crisis in psychology, the gut–brain connection, AI in hiring and decision-making, personality changes across the lifespan, and loneliness and social connection research.</p>
    <p>New classroom activities were also developed in response to faculty feedback. Several have quickly become favorites:</p>

    <div class="activity-grid">
      <div class="activity-card">
        <h3>Memory Championships</h3>
        <p>An in-class competition using evidence-based memory strategies, including a round where students try to memorize each other's names. Builds content knowledge and community.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="activity-card">
        <h3>Happiness Lab</h3>
        <p>Based on research from Berkeley's Greater Good Science Center, students learn about well-being practices and then actually try them. One of the most-loved activities in the course.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="activity-card">
        <h3>Fast Friends</h3>
        <p>Using Aron et al.'s 36 Questions for Increasing Closeness, students apply social psychology research while genuinely getting to know each other.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="activity-card">
        <h3>AI Study Partner</h3>
        <p>Students learn to use AI as a personalized study tool. Faculty reported that students found this genuinely eye-opening — many had never thought of AI as a learning partner before.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

